---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Evaluation Pipeline">
  <h1>Evaluation Pipeline</h1>

  <p>Every agent iteration runs through a multi-stage evaluation that measures both functional correctness and semantic quality.</p>

  <h2>Pipeline Stages</h2>
  <pre><code>Agent Code
    |
 TestGenerator - k test cases (LLM auto-generated)
    |
 TestRunner - exec each test via bun:eval
    |
 Schema validation - pass/fail per test
    |
 LLMJudge - semantic quality score (1-10 per criterion)
    |
 ScoreReport
    |
 Shadow Generalization - 3 unseen test cases
    |
 QualityGate - PASS or FAIL</code></pre>

  <h2>ScoreReport</h2>
  <pre><code>interface ScoreReport &lcub;
  testPassRate: number;       // 0.0 - 1.0
  judgeScore: number;          // 0.0 - 1.0
  composite: number;           // 0.6 * testPassRate + 0.4 * judgeScore
  generalizationScore: number or undefined; // from shadow eval (0.0 - 1.0)
  generalizationWarning: string or undefined;
  coverageGaps: string[];      // aspects of original intent not tested
  testResults: TestResult[];
  passed: boolean;
&rcub;</code></pre>

  <h2>Test Generation</h2>
  <p>Given the NL description and agent schemas, the LLM generates k=5 test cases that:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Cover all aspects of the original intent</li>
    <li>Include normal, edge, and error cases</li>
    <li>Are structurally diverse (Jaccard similarity enforced)</li>
    <li>Trace to description clauses for coverage tracking</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>TestRunner</h2>
  <p>Each test case is executed via <code>bun:eval</code> in an isolated subprocess:</p>
  <pre><code>// Agent code is loaded with a runtime shim
 import tools, handle from "agent-forge-runtime"
 agent code here

 // Test input is injected
 const input = &lcub; pr_url: "...", repo: "..." &rcub;;
 const result = await handle(input);

 // Output is validated against expected schema keys
 const hasKeys = expectedKeys.every(k returns k in result);</code></pre>

  <h2>LLM Judge</h2>
  <p>For each test output that parses, the LLM judge evaluates semantic quality:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Criterion</th><th>Score Range</th><th>What It Measures</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Correctness</td><td>0-25</td><td>Does the output correctly address the task?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Completeness</td><td>0-25</td><td>Are all required fields present and populated?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Quality</td><td>0-25</td><td>Is the output insightful and actionable?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Format Compliance</td><td>0-25</td><td>Does output match the expected schema?</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Judge score = average across criteria / 25</p>

  <h2>Composite Score</h2>
  <pre><code>composite = 0.6 * testPassRate + 0.4 * judgeScore</code></pre>
  <p>Weight ratio (60/40) favors functional correctness over stylistic quality.</p>

  <h2>Generalization Holdout</h2>
  <p>After the main eval passes, 3 additional shadow test cases run against the agent. These are unseen inputs within the intended scope but not similar to any training test case.</p>
  <p>If the agent fails the holdout, a warning is attached to the agent record but the agent still passes the gate. This guards against Goodhart's Law: optimizing to the test suite rather than the real use case.</p>
</Layout>
